Cursor adapter support

Redesign AsymmetricGridViewAdapter.

Turns AsymmetricGridViewAdapter into a wrapper that listens to changes
on the actual listView adapter and reacts to it, intead of holding its
own copy of the data. This allow more flexibility on user interaction,
allowing a CursorAdapter to be used for example. The demo app has been
updated accordingly to reflect the changes.

Allows using a WrapperListAdapter.

This change allows people to roll their own adapter and implement
WrapperListAdapter in order to provide the AsymmetricGridViewAdapter
functionality. Take a look in ListAdapterWrapper.java for a sample
implementation.
Tentative fix for layout save/restore issue

Fixes race condition on onRestoreInstanceState()

An incorrect ordering of restore state in onRestoreInstanceState
was causing an inconsistent layout after rotating the screen, for
example, due to an incorrect value for getNumColumns(). Moving the
adapter restoreState() call to the end should allow the listView to
restore itself first, then allow the adapter to restore and recalculate
the items per row.
fixes changelog format and deploy script
Small improvement to maven local deploy script

Adjustments to AsymmetricGridView.setAdapter()

- Removes duplicate definition of setAdapter due to different
 parameter types. It will now throw an exception if the view adapter
 doesn't implement the AsymmetricGridViewAdapterContract interface.

- Removes unused type parameter from AsymmetricGridView

- Creates AsymmetricGridViewAdapterContract which simplifies the
  required interface and makes it more flexible for implementers.
Updates buildToolsVersion, versionCode and readme caveats
Adds instructions for variable col/row span

Fixes ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException when rotating.

I suspect getView() was being called while ProcessRowsTask was running
in background. This could be calling a racing condition where getView()
was called before calculateItemsPerRow() had the chance to finish.

It's now cancelling the task if it is already running to prevent any
inconsistent state. Work in progress.
